[22:03:49    26] # Safety Plan
[22:03:49    26] 
[22:03:49    26] ## Completed
[22:03:49    26] 
[22:03:49    26] - Made hooks and parse-error state safe shared data (`Mutex` snapshots), and
[22:03:49    26]   converted parser input navigation, number/string encoding, lookup helpers,
[22:03:49    26]   and array-constructor input to safe references/slices where their ownership
[22:03:49    26]   permits it.
[22:03:49    26] - Removed several translated libc helpers and private raw-pointer facades.
[22:03:49    26]   Parser dispatch now accepts `&mut cJSON` parents; print helpers accept
[22:03:49    26]   `&mut printbuffer` rather than raw printbuffer pointers.
[22:03:49    26] - Preserved the C ABI, caller-buffer parse/error provenance, and custom hook
[22:03:49    26]   behavior. Each completed iteration was verified by `check-unsafe2` and all
[22:03:49    26]   translated C tests (18/18).
[22:03:49    26] 
[22:03:49    26] ## Completed this iteration
[22:03:49    26] 
[22:03:49    26] - `cJSON_New_Item` now returns `Option<NonNull<cJSON>>` instead of a raw
[22:03:49    26]   pointer. Its existing callers convert that safe internal result back to a
[22:03:49    26]   null raw pointer only at their C-facing linked-list/allocation boundaries.
[22:03:49    26]   This removes a raw pointer from an implementation function signature while
[22:03:49    26]   retaining hook allocation and failure behavior.
[22:03:49    26] - Removed the obsolete `raw_ref_op` feature gate; raw-reference syntax is
[22:03:49    26]   stable on the pinned compiler.
[22:03:49    26] 
[22:03:49    26] ## Broader blocker
[22:03:49    26] 
[22:03:49    26] - Re-audited the smallest remaining printer unit, `print_string_ptr`, and its
[22:03:49    26]   `printbuffer` callers. A safe printer would need both a safe owned output
[22:03:49    26]   buffer and a safe tree/string view. `printbuffer` is backed by the active C
[22:03:49    26]   allocator hook (or an FFI caller's preallocated byte buffer), while the
[22:03:49    26]   input comes from public `cJSON` raw string and linked-node fields. Neither
[22:03:49    26]   view can be formed in implementation code without raw conversion.
[22:03:49    26] - Confirmed the compatibility constraint rather than relying only on the
[22:03:49    26]   header: bundled C tests directly initialize and walk `child`, `next`, and
[22:03:49    26]   `prev`, and inspect `string`/`valuestring` (`tests/parse_object.c` and
[22:03:49    26]   `tests/misc_tests.c`). `cJSON` is therefore expressly non-opaque despite
[22:03:49    26]   being passed through pointers in the exported ABI. Replacing those fields
[22:03:49    26]   with `Box`/`Vec`/`Rc` would break supported C use and custom-hook ownership.
[22:03:49    26] - The eight implementation helpers reported by `check-unsafe2` (currently 60
[22:03:49    26]   findings)
[22:03:49    26]   are one compatibility cluster: `parse_string`, `print_string_ptr`,
[22:03:49    26]   `parse_value`, `print_value`, `parse_array`, `print_array`, `parse_object`,
[22:03:49    26]   and `print_object`. Parser allocation and printer traversal cannot be made
[22:03:49    26]   fully safe individually while retaining that public representation.
[22:03:49    26] - `check-unsafe2` also rejects newly introduced foreign-function uses even
[22:03:49    26]   when declared safe. Do not replace `parse_string`'s raw-slice write with new
