[22:06:55     4] - Preserved the C ABI, caller-buffer parse/error provenance, and custom hook
[22:06:55     4]   behavior. Each completed iteration was verified by `check-unsafe2` and all
[22:06:55     4]   translated C tests (18/18).
[22:06:55     4] 
[22:06:55     4] ## Completed in prior iterations
[22:06:55     4] 
[22:06:55     4] - `cJSON_New_Item` now returns `Option<NonNull<cJSON>>` instead of a raw
[22:06:55     4]   pointer. Its existing callers convert that safe internal result back to a
[22:06:55     4]   null raw pointer only at their C-facing linked-list/allocation boundaries.
[22:06:55     4]   This removes a raw pointer from an implementation function signature while
[22:06:55     4]   retaining hook allocation and failure behavior.
[22:06:55     4] - Removed the obsolete `raw_ref_op` feature gate; raw-reference syntax is
[22:07:45     4]   stable on the pinned compiler.
[22:07:45     4] 
[22:07:45     4] ## Blocker confirmed this iteration
[22:07:45     4] 
[22:07:45     4] - Re-audited the smallest remaining printer unit, `print_string_ptr`, and its
[22:07:45     4]   `printbuffer` callers. A safe printer would need both a safe owned output
[22:07:45     4]   buffer and a safe tree/string view. `printbuffer` is backed by the active C
[22:07:45     4]   allocator hook (or an FFI caller's preallocated byte buffer), while the
[22:07:45     4]   input comes from public `cJSON` raw string and linked-node fields. Neither
[22:07:45     4]   view can be formed in implementation code without raw conversion.
[22:07:45     4] - Confirmed the compatibility constraint rather than relying only on the
[22:07:45     4]   header: bundled C tests directly initialize and walk `child`, `next`, and
[22:07:45     4]   `prev`, and inspect `string`/`valuestring` (`tests/parse_object.c` and
[22:07:45     4]   `tests/misc_tests.c`). `cJSON` is therefore expressly non-opaque despite
[22:07:45     4]   being passed through pointers in the exported ABI. Replacing those fields
[22:07:45     4]   with `Box`/`Vec`/`Rc` would break supported C use and custom-hook ownership.
[22:07:45     4] - The checker attributes all remaining implementation-level unsafe work to
[22:07:45     4]   eight helpers (currently 60 total findings including FFI):
[22:07:45     4]   `parse_string`, `print_string_ptr`, `parse_value`, `print_value`,
[22:07:45     4]   `parse_array`, `print_array`, `parse_object`, and `print_object`.
[22:07:45     4]   These helpers are one compatibility cluster: `parse_string` must write into
[22:07:45     4]   hook-allocated storage; the parsers construct the C-visible linked nodes;
[22:07:45     4]   the printers read those nodes and C strings and write into hook/caller-owned
[22:07:45     4]   output storage. They cannot be split into safe pieces without changing the
[22:07:45     4]   public representation or allocator contract.
[22:07:45     4] - `check-unsafe2` also rejects newly introduced foreign-function uses even
[22:07:45     4]   when declared safe. Do not replace `parse_string`'s raw-slice write with new
[22:07:45     4]   `memcpy`/`memset` calls; that only relocates the unsafety and fails the
[22:07:45     4]   checker.
[22:07:45     4] 
[22:07:45     4] ## Remaining work / constraints
[22:07:45     4] 
[22:07:45     4] - This iteration made no Rust source change: re-auditing the smallest
[22:07:45     4]   remaining units (`parse_string`, `print_string_ptr`, and the linked-node
[22:07:45     4]   parse/print helpers) confirmed that `parse_string`'s raw-slice conversion
[22:07:45     4]   initializes hook-allocated storage, while printer input/output comes from
[22:07:45     4]   externally owned C memory. Replacing them with `Vec` changes the
[22:07:45     4]   allocation/free ABI; replacing them with `memcpy` adds an unsafe-adjacent
[22:07:45     4]   FFI import without making the allocation safe.
[22:07:45     4]   Remaining instances include `print_string_ptr` and parser/printer traversal
[22:07:45     4]   helpers.
[22:07:45     4]   They all stem from the C-visible `cJSON` raw linked-node/string fields and
[22:07:45     4]   hook-owned print/string allocations.
[22:07:45     4] - `cJSON` is explicitly public in `cJSON.h`, so its C layout and raw fields
[22:07:45     4]   cannot be changed as though opaque. Exported signatures must remain exact.
[22:07:45     4] - Do not copy parse input: parse-error and parse-end pointers must retain
[22:07:45     4]   caller-buffer provenance. Preserve BOM and end-whitespace handling.
[22:07:45     4] - Custom allocator hooks and reference/string-const flags are observable.
